, the eastern steppes, and other regions with strong local traditions, they were never effectively assimilated. And in cultures where there was a subtler blend of influences, notably in the Buddhist east, classical images served as a catalyst to the generation of new styles. Along the way, Boardman demonstrates that looking at Greek art from the outside provides a wealth of new insights into Greek art itself, and he raises important questions about how images in general are copied and reinterpreted.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertThe A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Packagez978311129290840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691252841?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691252841423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691252841/original  a978-3-11-129290-8  The A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles